7 years with his family-owned soft-drink-bottling franchise firm in the New York metropolitan area, during which he served tenure as president and [[Chief operating officer|COO]]; the company was sold in 1987.<ref name=\"forbes\"/>\n\n===Financial career===\nFollowing the sale of the family business, Bengen moved to Southern California and began a Certified Financial Planner practice, Bengen Financial Services, earning his certification in 1990 and his [[master's degree]] in [[financial plan]]ning in 1993. He ran the firm as a fee-only (no commission) practice for twenty years, then sold the firm and retired in 2013.<ref name=\"simonoff\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.fa-mag.com/news/bill-bengen--creator-of-the-4--retirement-rule--sells-firm-and-retires-15499.html | title=Bill Bengen, Creator Of The 4% Retirement Rule, Sells Firm And Retires |date=2013-09-18 |first=Evan |last=Simonoff |journal=Financial Advisor }}</ref>\n\n==The Four Percent Drawdown rule==\nBased on his early research of actual stock returns and retirement scenarios over the past 75 years, Bengen found that retirees who draw down no more than ''4.2 percent'' of their portfolio in the ''initial year'', and adjust that amount  ''every subsequent year for inflation'', stand a great chance their money will outlive them.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nelson|first=Colin|title=When Can I Tell My Boss, I Quit! : Seven Lessons for Financial and Personal Rebirth in Retirement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R_X5nGTA55UC&pg=PA122|year=2006|publisher=iUniverse|isbn=9780595827350|page=122}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ang|first=Andrew|title=Asset Management: A Systematic Approach to Factor Investing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ztvHAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA179|year=2014|publisher=Oxford UP|isbn=9780199382316|page=179}}</ref>\n\nThe 4% Rule is sometimes also called the Rule of 300. <ref>{{cite web|publisher=Finance Friday|url=https://thefinancefriday.com/2020/01/24/the-rule-of-300-best-way-to-retire/|title=THE RULE OF 300: THE BEST WAY TO RETIRE}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal |first=William P. |last=Bengen |url=http://www.retailinvestor.org/pdf/Bengen1.pdf |title=Determining Withdrawal Rates Using Historical Data |journal=Journal of Financial Planning | date=October  1994 |pages=14\u201324 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book | isbn = 978-0-97534483-5 | title = Conserving Client Portfolios During Retirement Paperback | last = Bengen | first = William P. | authorlink1 = William Bengen | year = 2006  | pages =  | ref = harv }} \n* {{cite journal |title=How Much Is Enough? |url=http://www.fa-mag.com/news/how-much-is-enough-10496.html |date=2012-05-01 |first=Bill |last=Bengen|ref=harv}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [http://www.investmentnews.com/article/20130606/FREE/130609969/15-transformational-advisers-william-p-bengen 15 transformational advisers: William P. Bengen], Jun 6, 2013, by Darla Mercado\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bengen, William}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American finance and investment writers]]\n[[Category:Financial advisors]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego County, California]]\n[[Category:Financial planners]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief operating officers]]\n", "name_user": "ViscountVismut", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling error now corrected!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Bengen"}
